music fans in Gainesville and afar. It is with the deepest sorrow that I share with you that our beloved music and events venue, High Dive, is coming to a sudden end. Our landlord informed us this week that we have 30 days to vacate the building and make way for a new owner who will redevelop the property. Attempts to prolong our exit date were not successful. \n\nWhile I knew this ending would one day come, I certainly did not think it would come so abruptly. The building has been for sale for many years, probably for close to half of our almost 13-year existence. Many potential sales have fallen through over the years, fueling many rumors. All along the way we have been under the impression that when the property was eventually sold we would receive ample notice with which to properly close out the business and give our community, performers and staff the chance to say their collective goodbyes. Unfortunately, things are coming to an end much sooner than expected.\n\nOUR FINAL SHOW WILL TAKE PLACE ON MAY 18TH OR MAY 19TH, 2024. ALL SHOWS UNTIL THAT DATE WILL OCCUR AS SCHEDULED. Please check our website at HighDiveGainesville.com. We also have a few dates still open on the calendar and would love to book a \u201clast show\u201d with old friends. I encourage everyone to come say goodbye to this local landmark one last time.\n\nWhile I am open-minded about finding the perfect location to relocate High Dive, I have not yet found that spot and have accepted the possibility of this being the end of the venue and the name. High Dive and Glory Days Presents! have a number of shows booked beyond the closing date that we are actively working to relocate to other venues. Everyone please hang tight as that is sorted out, we will be in touch very soon with more information.\n\nSince the early 90\u2019s (and under various names), High Dive has served as the reliable epicenter of Gainesville\u2019s music scene, a default tour stop for up-and-coming and midsize touring bands, and the place where every local band aspired to play once forming. Many local bands played their first, last and reunion shows here. Sometimes even huge artists like Kenny Chesney, local legend and Rock N Roll Hall of Famer Mike Campbell (Heartbreakers), and (soon) Sunny Day Real Estate would stop in and pay tribute to its historic stage. \n\nI began working at the (then) Covered Dish at 210 SW 2nd Ave around 1998 as the flyer guy, stapling show flyers to bulletin boards on the University of FL campus and taping them to telephone poles up and down University and 13th in between classes. By far the best perk of the job was free admission to every show. This is where I got my masters in underground rock music, absorbing the culture and knowledge about little-known bands on a nightly basis. After owner Bill Bryson closed the Dish in 2000, the building was a couple of different dance clubs until Common Grounds re-opened it as a live music venue around 2005. A few years later, I began organizing shows there under my recently formed concert promotions company Glory Days Presents! At the time, I had been promoting some quality shows for good bands, albeit at a hodgepodge of dead-end venues. Booking shows at Common Grounds was like getting a call to the big leagues of the local music scene. This relationship proved to be mutually beneficial \u2013 both prolonging the life of the venue and allowing me to further hone my craft and build my promotions company. Some highlight shows from that time period include The Avett Brothers, Streetlight Manifesto, The Lemonheads, Bayside, JJ Grey & Mofro, Mayday Parade, The Weakerthans, The Walkmen, my first nationally touring stand-up comedy shows with Brian Posehn and Doug Benson, and a last-minute benefit show with Sister Hazel. In 2011, when Common Grounds\u2019s owners Nigel Hamm and Jason Rockhill decided that the venue had run its course, they \u201cpassed the torch\u201d to me as the next proprietor of the building. While I was at first hesitant to take on this responsibility, I am eternally grateful for their wisdom and assistance in ushering in that transition.   \n\nSince 2011, High Dive has sought to continue and improve on the tradition of being Gainesville\u2019s professional neighborhood rock club. A place where all types of people could feel welcome to witness and perform all types of music without pretense, on a big stage with a killer sound system. Over time, we evolved to regularly present comedy, theater, food truck rallies, dance parties, private events, and all sorts of other gatherings. We were a local launching pad for the careers of bands like flipturn, The Hails, Arrows in Action, Revivalists, Lindsey Stirling, Stick Figure, Big Freedia, Japanese Breakfast, Mitski, JID, The Struts, Matt Maeson, Ethel Cain, Strfkr, Declan McKenna, Beach Fossils, The 502\u2019s, Megan Maroney, Muscadine Bloodline, Marcus King, Michael Ray, Blackberry Smoke, Amigo the Devil, Clozee, Moon Hooch, Durand Jones, TWRP, Puddles Pity Party, Kyle Kinane, Chris Renzema and many more artists who played their first shows in Gainesville with us. We have also been extremely fortunate to host so many \u201cbucket list\u201d type acts like Henry Rollins, Eric Andre, Kevin Smith, Black Flag, Built to Spill, Lucero, Me First and the Gimme Gimme\u2019s, Laura Jane Grace, Reel Big Fish, Less Than Jake, Chuck Ragan, The Get Up Kids, Andrew WK, Motion City Soundtrack, Frank Iero of My Chemical Romance, New Found Glory, Everclear, Eve 6, Cracker, Sponge, Mike Watt, Frank Turner, Amy Ray of the Indigo Girls, Bone Thugs N Harmony, Ying Yang Twins, The Wailers, Dick Dale, and The Melvins. Guitar virtuoso Buckethead once declared us one of his favorite venues to play in the country! The music publication Consequence listed High Dive as one of the \u201c100 Greatest American Music Venues\u201d. I couldn\u2019t have been more proud.\n\nThe past 13 years have been nothing short of an adventure, oftentimes punishing and humbling but also greatly rewarding and full of joy. Many mistakes were made, and countless rewards were savored, if only briefly. It was our duty to uphold the tradition of our location and the drive to serve the Gainesville music community that helped us persevere through all the challenges. Personally, I have spent almost my entire adult life working in this building and am deeply saddened that it will not continue. Ironically, the last few years, despite the very challenging times we all find ourselves in, have been some of the best we have experienced. Only an outside force like gentrification could knock this train off its track. With that in mind, I must thank all the performers, endless supporters, and dedicated staff past and present who helped make High Dive what it is.\n\nUltimately, it\u2019s my goal to continue bringing memorable shows to Gainesville for many years to come, whether that be at existing venues, a re-imagined High Dive, or a similar new venue. As Gainesville is changing rapidly around us, it is my sincere hope that those who love it will continue to fight to preserve our rich cultural history, which has made Gainesville such a unique place to call home.\n\nThank you all,\n\nPat Lavery\nFounder and owner, High Dive 2011 \u2013 2024\nGlory Days Presents"},"message_truncation_line_limit":null,"sponsored_data":null,"attachments":[{"action_links":[{"__typename":"MMEMessengerActionLink","url":null}]}],"id":"UzpfSTEwMDA4MDAwOTI1NzgxMDo0NjAwODA5OTY2Njg4NzI6NDYwMDgwOTk2NjY4ODcy"},"__module_operation_CometFeedStoryMessageMatchRenderer_story":{"__dr":"CometFeedStoryDefaultMessageRenderingStrategy_message$normalization.graphql"},"__module_component_CometFeedStoryMessageMatchRenderer_story":{"__dr":"CometFeedStoryDefaultMessageRenderingStrategy.react"}},"message_suffix":null,"message_container":{"__typename":"CometFeedStoryMessageContainerRenderingStrategy","__isICometStorySection":"CometFeedStoryMessageContainerRenderingStrategy","is_prod_eligible":true,"story":{"message":{"text":"Hello music fans in Gainesville and afar. Days Presents - Gainesville, FL","__isEntity":"User","url":"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/glorydaysGNV"}],"message":{"__typename":"TextWithEntities","text":"Hello music fans in Gainesville and afar. It is with the deepest sorrow that I share with you that our beloved music and events venue, High Dive, is coming to a sudden end. Our landlord informed us this week that we have 30 days to vacate the building and make way for a new owner who will redevelop the property. Attempts to prolong our exit date were not successful. \n\nWhile I knew this ending would one day come, I certainly did not think it would come so abruptly. The building has been for sale for many years, probably for close to half of our almost 13-year existence. Many potential sales have fallen through over the years, fueling many rumors. All along the way we have been under the impression that when the property was eventually sold we would receive ample notice with which to properly close out the business and give our community, performers and staff the chance to say their collective goodbyes. Unfortunately, things are coming to an end much sooner than expected.\n\nOUR FINAL SHOW WILL TAKE PLACE ON MAY 18TH OR MAY 19TH, 2024. ALL SHOWS UNTIL THAT DATE WILL OCCUR AS SCHEDULED. Please check our website at HighDiveGainesville.com. We also have a few dates still open on the calendar and would love to book a \u201clast show\u201d with old friends. I encourage everyone to come say goodbye to this local landmark one last time.\n\nWhile I am open-minded about finding the perfect location to relocate High Dive, I have not yet found that spot and have accepted the possibility of this being the end of the venue and the name. High Dive and Glory Days Presents! have a number of shows booked beyond the closing date that we are actively working to relocate to other venues. Everyone please hang tight as that is sorted out, we will be in touch very soon with more information.\n\nSince the early 90\u2019s (and under various names), High Dive has served as the reliable epicenter of Gainesville\u2019s music scene, a default tour stop for up-and-coming and midsize touring bands, and the place where every local band aspired to play once forming. Many local bands played their first, last and reunion shows here. Sometimes even huge artists like Kenny Chesney, local legend and Rock N Roll Hall of Famer Mike Campbell (Heartbreakers), and (soon) Sunny Day Real Estate would stop in and pay tribute to its historic stage. \n\nI began working at the (then) Covered Dish at 210 SW 2nd Ave around 1998 as the flyer guy, stapling show flyers to bulletin boards on the University of FL campus and taping them to telephone poles up and down University and 13th in between classes. By far the best perk of the job was free admission to every show. This is where I got my masters in underground rock music, absorbing the culture and knowledge about little-known bands on a nightly basis. After owner Bill Bryson closed the Dish in 2000, the building was a couple of different dance clubs until Common Grounds re-opened it as a live music venue around 2005. A few years later, I began organizing shows there under my recently formed concert promotions company Glory Days Presents! At the time, I had been promoting some quality shows for good bands, albeit at a hodgepodge of dead-end venues. Booking shows at Common Grounds was like getting a call to the big leagues of the local music scene. This relationship proved to be mutually beneficial \u2013 both prolonging the life of the venue and allowing me to further hone my craft and build my promotions company. Some highlight shows from that time period include The Avett Brothers, Streetlight Manifesto, The Lemonheads, Bayside, JJ Grey & Mofro, Mayday Parade, The Weakerthans, The Walkmen, my first nationally touring stand-up comedy shows with Brian Posehn and Doug Benson, and a last-minute benefit show with Sister Hazel. In 2011, when Common Grounds\u2019s owners Nigel Hamm and Jason Rockhill decided that the venue had run its course, they \u201cpassed the torch\u201d to me as the next proprietor of the building. While I was at first hesitant to take on this responsibility, I am eternally grateful for their wisdom and assistance in ushering in that transition.   \n\nSince 2011, High Dive has sought to continue and improve on the tradition of being Gainesville\u2019s professional neighborhood rock club. A place where all types of people could feel welcome to witness and perform all types of music without pretense, on a big stage with a killer sound system. Over time, we evolved to regularly present comedy, theater, food truck rallies, dance parties, private events, and all sorts of other gatherings. We were a local launching pad for the careers of bands like flipturn, The Hails, Arrows in Action, Revivalists, Lindsey Stirling, Stick Figure, Big Freedia, Japanese Breakfast, Mitski, JID, The Struts, Matt Maeson, Ethel Cain, Strfkr, Declan McKenna, Beach Fossils, The 502\u2019s, Megan Maroney, Muscadine Bloodline, Marcus King, Michael Ray, Blackberry Smoke, Amigo the Devil, Clozee, Moon Hooch, Durand Jones, TWRP, Puddles Pity Party, Kyle Kinane, Chris Renzema and many more artists who played their first shows in Gainesville with us. We have also been extremely fortunate to host so many \u201cbucket list\u201d type acts like Henry Rollins, Eric Andre, Kevin Smith, Black Flag, Built to Spill, Lucero, Me First and the Gimme Gimme\u2019s, Laura Jane Grace, Reel Big Fish, Less Than Jake, Chuck Ragan, The Get Up Kids, Andrew WK, Motion City Soundtrack, Frank Iero of My Chemical Romance, New Found Glory, Everclear, Eve 6, Cracker, Sponge, Mike Watt, Frank Turner, Amy Ray of the Indigo Girls, Bone Thugs N Harmony, Ying Yang Twins, The Wailers, Dick Dale, and The Melvins. Guitar virtuoso Buckethead once declared us one of his favorite venues to play in the country! The music publication Consequence listed High Dive as one of the \u201c100 Greatest American Music Venues\u201d. I couldn\u2019t have been more proud.\n\nThe past 13 years have been nothing short of an adventure, oftentimes punishing and humbling but also greatly rewarding and full of joy. Many mistakes were made, and countless rewards were savored, if only briefly. It was our duty to uphold the tradition of our location and the drive to serve the Gainesville music community that helped us persevere through all the challenges. Personally, I have spent almost my entire adult life working in this building and am deeply saddened that it will not continue. Ironically, the last few years, despite the very challenging times we all find ourselves in, have been some of the best we have experienced. Only an outside force like gentrification could knock this train off its track. With that in mind, I must thank all the performers, endless supporters, and dedicated staff past and present who helped make High Dive what it is.\n\nUltimately, it\u2019s my goal to continue bringing memorable shows to Gainesville for many years to come, whether that be at existing venues, a re-imagined High Dive, or a similar new venue. As Gainesville is changing rapidly around us, it is my sincere hope that those who love it will continue to fight to preserve our rich cultural history, which has made Gainesville such a unique place to call home.\n\nThank you all,\n\nPat Lavery\nFounder and owner, High Dive 2011 \u2013 2024\nGlory Days x1vvkbs x126k92a"><div dir="auto" style="text-align:start">Hello music fans in Gainesville and afar. It is with the deepest sorrow that I share with you that our beloved music and events venue, High Dive, is coming to a sudden end. Our landlord informed us this week that we have 30 days to vacate the building and make way for a new owner who will redevelop the property. Attempts to prolong our exit date were not successful. </div></div><div class="x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak x1vvkbs xtlvy1s x126k92a"><div dir="auto" style="text-align:start">While I knew this ending would one day come, I certainly did not think it would come so abruptly. The building has been for sale for many years, probably for close to half of our almost 13-year existence. Many potential sales have fallen through over the years, fueling many rumors. All along the way we have been under the impression that when the property was eventually sold we would receive ample notice with which to properly close out the business and give our community, performers and staff the chance to say their collective goodbyes. Unfortunately, things are coming to an end much sooner than expected.</div></div><div class="x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak x1vvkbs xtlvy1s x126k92a"><div dir="auto" style="text-align:start">OUR FINAL SHOW WILL TAKE PLACE ON MAY 18TH OR MAY 19TH, 2024. ALL SHOWS UNTIL THAT DATE WILL OCCUR AS SCHEDULED. I encourage everyone to come say goodbye to this local landmark one last time.</div></div><div class="x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak x1vvkbs xtlvy1s x126k92a"><div dir="auto" style="text-align:start">While I am open-minded about finding the perfect location to relocate High Dive, I have not yet found that spot and have accepted the possibility of this being the end of the venue and the name. High Dive and Glory Days Presents! have a number of shows booked beyond the closing date that we are actively working to relocate to other venues. Everyone please hang tight as that is sorted out, we will be in touch very soon with more information.</div></div><div class="x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak x1vvkbs xtlvy1s x126k92a"><div dir="auto" style="text-align:start">Since the early 90s (and under various names), High Dive has served as the reliable epicenter of Gainesvilles music scene, a default tour stop for up-and-coming and midsize touring bands, and the place where every local band aspired to play once forming. Many local bands played their first, last and reunion shows here. Sometimes even huge artists like Kenny Chesney, local legend and Rock N Roll Hall of Famer Mike Campbell (Heartbreakers), and (soon) Sunny Day Real Estate would stop in and pay tribute to its historic stage. </div></div><div class="x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak x1vvkbs xtlvy1s x126k92a"><div dir="auto" style="text-align:start">I began working at the (then) Covered Dish at 210 SW 2nd Ave around 1998 as the flyer guy, stapling show flyers to bulletin boards on the University of FL campus and taping them to telephone poles up and down University and 13th in between classes. By far the best perk of the job was free admission to every show. This is where I got my masters in underground rock music, absorbing the culture and knowledge about little-known bands on a nightly basis. After owner Bill Bryson closed the Dish in 2000, the building was a couple of different dance clubs until Common Grounds re-opened it as a live music venue around 2005. A few years later, I began organizing shows there under my recently formed concert promotions company Glory Days Presents! At the time, I had been promoting some quality shows for good bands, albeit at a hodgepodge of dead-end venues. Booking shows at Common Grounds was like getting a call to the big leagues of the local music scene. This relationship proved to be mutually beneficial  both prolonging the life of the venue and allowing me to further hone my craft and build my promotions company. Some highlight shows from that time period include The Avett Brothers, Streetlight Manifesto, The Lemonheads, Bayside, JJ Grey & Mofro, Mayday Parade, The Weakerthans, The Walkmen, my first nationally touring stand-up comedy shows with Brian Posehn and Doug Benson, and a last-minute benefit show with Sister Hazel. In 2011, when Common Groundss owners Nigel Hamm and Jason Rockhill decided that the venue had run its course, they passed the torch to me as the next proprietor of the building. While I was at first hesitant to take on this responsibility, I am eternally grateful for their wisdom and assistance in ushering in that transition.   </div></div><div class="x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak x1vvkbs xtlvy1s x126k92a"><div dir="auto" style="text-align:start">Since 2011, High Dive has sought to continue and improve on the tradition of being Gainesvilles professional neighborhood rock club. A place where all types of people could feel welcome to witness and perform all types of music without pretense, on a big stage with a killer sound system. Over time, we evolved to regularly present comedy, theater, food truck rallies, dance parties, private events, and all sorts of other gatherings. We were a local launching pad for the careers of bands like flipturn, The Hails, Arrows in Action, Revivalists, Lindsey Stirling, Stick Figure, Big Freedia, Japanese Breakfast, Mitski, JID, The Struts, Matt Maeson, Ethel Cain, Strfkr, Declan McKenna, Beach Fossils, The 502s, Megan Maroney, Muscadine Bloodline, Marcus King, Michael Ray, Blackberry Smoke, Amigo the Devil, Clozee, Moon Hooch, Durand Jones, TWRP, Puddles Pity Party, Kyle Kinane, Chris Renzema and many more artists who played their first shows in Gainesville with us. We have also been extremely fortunate to host so many bucket list type acts like Henry Rollins, Eric Andre, Kevin Smith, Black Flag, Built to Spill, Lucero, Me First and the Gimme Gimmes, Laura Jane Grace, Reel Big Fish, Less Than Jake, Chuck Ragan, The Get Up Kids, Andrew WK, Motion City Soundtrack, Frank Iero of My Chemical Romance, New Found Glory, Everclear, Eve 6, Cracker, Sponge, Mike Watt, Frank Turner, Amy Ray of the Indigo Girls, Bone Thugs N Harmony, Ying Yang Twins, The Wailers, Dick Dale, and The Melvins. Guitar virtuoso Buckethead once declared us one of his favorite venues to play in the country! The music publication Consequence listed High Dive as one of the 100 Greatest American Music Venues. I couldnt have been more proud.</div></div><div class="x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak x1vvkbs xtlvy1s x126k92a"><div dir="auto" style="text-align:start">The past 13 years have been nothing short of an adventure, oftentimes punishing and humbling but also greatly rewarding and full of joy. Many mistakes were made, and countless rewards were savored, if only briefly. It was our duty to uphold the tradition of our location and the drive to serve the Gainesville music community that helped us persevere through all the challenges. Personally, I have spent almost my entire adult life working in this building and am deeply saddened that it will not continue. Ironically, the last few years, despite the very challenging times we all find ourselves in, have been some of the best we have experienced. Only an outside force like gentrification could knock this train off its track. With that in mind, I must thank all the performers, endless supporters, and dedicated staff past and present who helped make High Dive what it is.</div></div><div class="x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak x1vvkbs xtlvy1s x126k92a"><div dir="auto" style="text-align:start">Ultimately, its my goal to continue bringing memorable shows to Gainesville for many years to come, whether that be at existing venues, a re-imagined High Dive, or a similar new venue. As Gainesville is changing rapidly around us, it is my sincere hope that those who love it will continue to fight to preserve our rich cultural history, which has made Gainesville such a unique place to call home.</div></div><div class="x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak x1vvkbs xtlvy1s x126k92a"><div dir="auto" style="text-align:start">Thank you all,</div></div><div class="x14z9mp xat24cr x1lziwak x1vvkbs
